{"schema_version": 2, "ts": "2026-05-11T12:42:25Z", "event": "clarify_critic", "feature": "extract-conditional-content-blocks-to-references-a-b-downgrade-rubric-implement-daytime-trimmed-scope", "parent_epic_loaded": true, "findings": [{"text": "The line range '212\u2013260' cited in the ticket for the critical-review/SKILL.md 8 worked examples is wrong on inspection; worked examples 1\u20136 live at lines 229\u2013266 and worked examples 7\u20138 live at lines 267\u2013281, so the ticket's literal line range excludes 2 of the 8 examples it names.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "Trigger-prose placement for the critical-review extraction is unspecified \u2014 the 8 worked examples live inside the synthesizer prompt template that is dispatched to a sub-agent, and the ticket does not say whether the 'read references/...' instruction goes in the synthesizer template, above the rubric heading, or in SKILL.md's Contents.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment's HIGH boundedness rating relies on line-count gates (implement.md ~210, critical-review/SKILL.md ~315) whose baselines (286, 365) do not match the actual on-disk state (302, 369).", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "Calling scope 'extraction only \u2014 not refactoring the conditional logic itself' undercounts the verification surface; the ticket itself requires a fresh daytime-dispatch run to verify trigger-prose loading behavior under Opus 4.7, which is behavioral verification, not mechanical extraction.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "Requirements alignment is asserted as HIGH on the basis that project.md endorses extraction to references/, but project.md frames that as the 'default remediation' when files exceed the 500-line cap \u2014 and neither targeted file (302, 369) is over the cap, so the cited rule's conditional is elided.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The assessment claims the trimmed scope mitigates the Medium-rated parity-test cost, but the trim removed only the riskiest single item \u2014 the per-extraction parity-test cost remains for the 2 kept extractions (4 new mirror entries, 2 new drift checks, 2 new edit-coordination cases).", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The complex-tier rating cites the same risk family (dual-source enforcement, trigger-prose verification under Opus 4.7, no test design for conditional split correctness) that the ticket uses to defer 4 of 6 sibling extractions; the assessment doesn't reconcile why the same risk class is decisive for the deferred four and merely a tier-bump for the kept-in two.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The verification protocol covers only one happy-path runtime check (daytime-dispatch loads references/implement-daytime.md); there is no equivalent negative or positive case for the a-b-downgrade-rubric trigger, leaving silent trigger-prose failure undetectable for that extraction.", "origin": "primary"}, {"text": "The parent epic body characterizes implement.md \u00a71a as 'harness-level logic\u2026 mostly duplicating cortex_command/overnight/daytime_pipeline.py' \u2014 i.e., a duplication problem to be resolved \u2014 but this child ticket's remedy is to relocate the \u00a71a content wholesale into a new reference file, which moves the duplication rather than eliminating it; a research consideration is whether \u00a71a is more cleanly addressed as a thin pointer to the Python module rather than relocated into a new reference file.", "origin": "alignment"}], "dispositions": {"apply": 5, "dismiss": 3, "ask": 0}, "applied_fixes": ["Corrected the line range for the critical-review extraction: actual span of the 8 worked examples is lines 229\u2013281 (~49 lines), not 212\u2013260; verification targets will be recomputed against the actual span at implementation time.", "Calibrated baseline line counts to current on-disk state: implement.md = 302 lines and critical-review/SKILL.md = 369 lines (not 286/365); verification targets adjust accordingly (~226 and ~320 post-extraction).", "Added trigger-prose behavioral verification to scope \u2014 the boundary is two extractions, but each carries a runtime-load verification component, not extraction-only.", "Revised requirements alignment from 'Aligned' to 'Partial alignment': project.md frames extraction primarily as cap-remediation for files over the 500-line cap; this ticket extends the same pattern to sub-cap files (302, 369) for hot-path context savings, which is a documented project goal but not the cited rule's primary use case.", "Added an open question for research: how should the a-b-downgrade-rubric trigger behavior be verified end-to-end, given the consumer is a sub-agent reading a synthesizer prompt template?"], "dismissals": [{"finding_index": 1, "rationale": "Trigger-prose placement is a HOW question that capable models resolve from existing in-repo patterns (per project rule: specify decisions/gates/intent, not procedural method). Research will surface the placement convention from existing extractions."}, {"finding_index": 5, "rationale": "The Medium-rated parity-test cost was already weighed in the epic-172-audit C7 reversal that produced the trimmed scope ('Halved to the 2 cleanest extractions for ~1/3 the maintenance burden'); the cost-vs-savings trade was the basis for trimming from 6 to 2, not a residual to re-litigate now."}, {"finding_index": 6, "rationale": "The ticket's 'Why kept (vs deferred)' table column explicitly distinguishes the kept-in trigger conditions (user-gated unambiguous; single clean conditional fired during a specific synthesis subtask) from the deferred ones (re-entrant logic intertwined; concurrent-lifecycle gate prose unreliable under Opus 4.7 literalism); the assessment doesn't fail to reconcile \u2014 the reconciliation is in the source material."}], "status": "ok"}
